'''Colored coins''' are a class of methods for associating real world [[asset]]s with addresses on the [[bitcoin network]]. Examples could be a [[deed]] for a house, [[stock]]s, [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] or [[Futures contract|futures]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradbury|first1=Danny|title=Colored coins paint sophisticated future for Bitcoin|url=http://www.coindesk.com/colored-coins-paint-sophisticated-future-for-bitcoin/|accessdate=20 December 2015|date=14 June 2013}}</ref> The technology could also be used to track and register [[intellectual property]] assets.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maras|first1=Elliot|title=Report: How The Blockchain Will Revolutionize Charitable Giving|url=https://www.cryptocoinsnews.com/report-block-chain-will-revolutionize-charitable-giving/|accessdate=20 December 2015|date=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bartlett|first1=Jamie|title=Imogen Heap: saviour of the music industry?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/sep/06/imogen-heap-saviour-of-music-industry|accessdate=20 December 2015|date=6 September 2015}}</ref>
Through 2014/15 it was suggested that various coloured coin protocols could be of interest to [[bank]]s and major [[financial institution]]s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rizzo|first1=Pete|title=New Colored Coins Implementation Released After Standard Drive Abandoned|url=http://www.coindesk.com/colu-colored-coins-implementation-standard-abandoned/|accessdate=20 December 2015|date=24 June 2015}}</ref> This prediction came true in June 2015 when NASDAQ announced they were developing a system in partnership with blockchain startup Chain using the Open Assets protocol developed and utilised by CoinPrism and built on by Get Hashing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rizzo|first1=Pete|title=Chain CEO: Nasdaq Partnership is No PR Stunt|url=http://www.coindesk.com/chain-nasdaq-partnership-pr-stunt/|accessdate=22 January 2016|date=25 June 2015}}</ref> In late 2015 NASDAQ announced that the first ever trade had occurred using its new platform, Linq.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nasdaq Linq Enables First-Ever Private Securities Issuance Documented With Blockchain Technology|url=http://ir.nasdaq.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=948326|accessdate=22 January 2016|date=30 December 2015}}</ref>
There are several competing implementations of the coloured coins idea, using differing methods, including those developed by CoinSpark, Colu and several built on the EPBOC protocol.
Colored Coins was invented by [[Yoni Assia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Yoni Assia|url=https://blockchainbios.com/yoniassia.html|author=T. Wassenaar|accessdate=2 October 2018|website=[[Github]]|quote=He is also the inventor of bitcoin 2.0’s Colored Coins}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=eToro CEO Joins Board at Bitcoin Startup Colu|url=https://www.coindesk.com/etoro-board-director-bitcoin-startu-colu/|author=Pete Rizzo|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=2 October 2018|website=[[CoinDesk]]|quote=Assia is credited as one of the originators of the concept of colored coins}}</ref>
