{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use British English|date=April 2018}} {{Orphan|date=September 2016}} '''Daniel Delander''' (died 1733), also known as De Lander or Delaunder, was a notable London clock and watch maker coming from a dynasty of clockmakers.
== Biography == Successor to Nathaniel Delander, Daniel Delander was apprenticed in 1692 to Charles Halstead and, later, to [[Thomas Tompion]]; he became a member of the [[Clockmakers' Company]] in 1699.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=uuA1AQAAMAAJ&lpg=PA106&ots=pH-fF7ildZ&dq=Daniel%20Delander%20English%20clockmaker&pg=PA106#v=onepage&q&f=false Old English Clocks (the Wetherfield Collection) by David Arthur Fasham Wetherfield]</ref> He opened his own shop at the Dial in [[Devereux Court]] in 1706 and worked there until 1712. Then he relocated to [[Temple Bar, London|Two Temple Gates]] where he stayed until 1717, and finally he moved to [[Fleet Street]], where he toiled until his death in 1733. Delander invented the lock spring for securing watch cases and was the first to produce an independent centre seconds stopwatch.<ref>[http://www.walwynantiqueclocks.com/clock-news/a-biography-of-the-clockmaker-daniel-delander-2670 A biography of the clockmaker Daniel Delander], 26 August 2015.</ref> Delander also built many [[mantel clock]]s and [[longcase clock]]s. His son Nathaniel Delander II continued the family tradition.
== Legacy == There are clocks by Delander at the [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]] and [[Guildhall, London|Guildhall Museum]] in [[London]] and at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Dd_WCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA150&ots=7k0mx7ZOcD&dq=Daniel%20Delander%20English%20clockmaker&pg=PA150#v=onepage&q&f=false European Clocks and Watches in The Metropolitan Museum of Art by Clare Vincent and Jan Hendrik Leopold]</ref> The [[British Museum]] (Ilbert Collection) has the oldest independent-seconds watch, built by Delander in 1720.<ref>[[Museo Galileo]]. "[http://catalogue.museogalileo.it/biography/DanielDelander.html ''Daniel Delander'']". Catalogue of the Museo Galileo's Instruments on Display. ''catalogue.museogalileo.it''</ref>
