'''John Tilton Hack''' (1913–1991) was an American [[geologist]] and [[geomorphology|geomorphologist]] known for his contributions to establish the dynamic equilibrium concept in landscapes. He was a student of [[Kirk Bryan (geologist)|Kirk Bryan]]. He retired from the [[United States Geological Survey]] in 1981.<ref>{{cite journal|author-last=Osterkamp|author-first=W.R.|author-last2=Hupp|author-first2=C.R.|title=Memorial to John T. Hack|url=ftp://rock.geosociety.org/pub/Memorials/v23/Hack-JT.pdf|journal=Memorials|volume=23|pages=59–61}}</ref>

Hack graduated from [[Harvard University]], where he received his bachelors and master's degrees and doctorate in geomorphology.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1991/12/20/geologist-john-t-hack-dies-at-78/71654b29-e942-43ea-8bf8-0c7ebac544f3/ Obituary]</ref>

