{{Chembox | ImageFile = Sr_2_Ru_O_4_Layered_Perovskite_Structure.svg | ImageSize =240px | ImageAlt = LBCO unit cell | ImageCaption = The unit cell of the layered perovskite structure of LBCO. Copper ions are red, lanthanum (barium) ions are blue, and oxygen ions are green. |Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers }}}}
'''Lanthanum barium copper oxide''', or LBCO, was discovered in 1986 and was the first [[High-temperature superconductivity|high temperature superconductor]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = J. G. Bednorz and K. A. Müller | title = Possible high T<sub>c</sub> superconductivity in the Ba−La−Cu−O system | journal = Z. Phys. B | volume = 64 | year = 1986 | pages = 189–193 | doi = 10.1007/BF01303701 | issue = 1 | bibcode=1986ZPhyB..64..189B}}</ref> [[Johannes Georg Bednorz]] and [[Karl Alexander Müller|K. Alex Müller]] shared the 1987 [[Nobel Prize]] in [[physics]] for its discovery.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hazen|first1=Robert M.|author-link=Robert Hazen|title=The breakthrough : the race for the superconductor|page=255|date=1988|publisher=Summit Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0671658298}}</ref>
