The Social and Behavioral Sciences Team (SBST) was established in the US by [[Executive order|Executive Order]] #[https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2015/09/18/2015-23630/using-behavioral-science-insights-to-better-serve-the-american-people 13707] on September 15, 2015.{{Infobox Government agency |name=Social and Behavioral Sciences Team|seal=US-OfficeOfScienceAndTechnologyPolicy-Seal.svg|logo=|formed=September 15, 2015|jurisdiction=Government of the United States of America|employees=|budget= |chief1_name = [[Maya Shankar]] |chief1_position = Chair |chief2_name = Amira Choueiki |chief2_position=Executive Secretary |chief3_name=|chief3_position=|chief4_name=|chief4_position=|chief5_name=|chief5_position=|chief6_name=|chief6_position=|chief7_name=|chief7_position=|chief8_name=|chief8_position=|chief9_name=|chief9_position=|parent_department=[[Executive Office of the President]]|website={{URL|https://SBST.Gov/}} |parent_agency=[[National Science and Technology Council]]|headquarters=725 17th Street, Washington, D.C.}}
The '''Social and Behavioral Sciences Team''' is a group of experts in applied behavioral science that translates findings and methods from the social and behavioral sciences into improvements in Federal policies and programs for the benefit of the American people. The SBST is chaired by the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy (OSTP) and represents a dozen member agencies across the Federal Government, as well as offices within the Executive Office of the President. SBST also receives critical support from the General Services Administration. The Executive Order charges SBST with providing advice and policy guidance to Federal agencies in support of the order.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/09/15/fact-sheet-president-obama-signs-executive-order-white-house-announces|title=Fact Sheet: President Obama Signs Executive Order; White House Announces New Steps to Improve Federal Programs by Leveraging Research Insights|date=2015-09-15|newspaper=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref>
The team was chaired by [[Maya Shankar]] Ph.D.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sbst.gov/download/2015%20SBST%20Annual%20Report.pdf|title=Social and Behavioral Sciences Team Annual Report 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> "The goal is to help people who want to take a given step but may face some barriers," commented [[Maya Shankar|Maya]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/30/business/behaviorists-show-the-us-how-to-improve-government-operations.html|title=Behaviorists Show the U.S. How to Improve Government Operations|last=Appelbaum|first=Binyamin|date=2015-09-29|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref> The team is no longer active as of January 21, 2017, with employees having left to other agencies or organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/01/23/can-behavioral-science-help-in-flint|title=Can Behavioral Science Help in Flint?|website=The New Yorker|access-date=2017-08-08}}</ref>
The SBST aimed to apply insights from [[social and behavioral science]] to policy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4042689/social-behavioral-sciences-team/|title=The White House Is Now Using Behavioral Economics to Improve Policy|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name="MyUser_Https:_January_18_2016c">{{cite web |url=https://sbst.gov/2015-annual-report/ |title=2015 Annual Report |newspaper=Https: |date= |author= |accessdate= January 18, 2016}}</ref> It has helped connect veterans with employment and educational counseling benefits and helped struggling student borrowers understand their loan repayment options.<ref name="WHITEHOUSE2">{{cite web |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2015/02/09/behavioral-science-insights-make-government-more-effective-simpler-and-more-user-fri |title=Using Behavioral Science Insights to Make Government More Effective, Simpler, and More People-Friendly |newspaper= |date= |author= |accessdate= January 18, 2016}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=January 2016}}
